{{speciesbox | image =Greenheart (13927555000).jpg | status = DD | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref = <ref name=iucn/> | genus = Chlorocardium | species = rodiei | authority = (M.R.Schomb.) Rohwer et al. | synonyms = * ''Nectandra rodiei'' * ''Ocotea rodiei'' }}
'''''Chlorocardium rodiei''''' ('''greenheart''') is a species of flowering plant in the family [[Lauraceae]]. It is one of two species in the genus ''[[Chlorocardium]]''. It is native [[Guyana]] and [[Suriname]] in [[South America]].<ref name=iucn>Red List Standards & Petitions Working Group. 2007. [http://www.iucnredlist.org/details/34688/0 ''Chlorocardium rodiei''.] In: IUCN 2013. IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. Version 2013.1. Downloaded on 24 July 2013.</ref> Other common names include '''cogwood''', '''demerara greenheart''', '''''ispingo moena''''',<ref name=iucn/> '''''sipiri''''', '''''bebeeru''''' and '''''bibiru'''''.
It is an [[evergreen]] [[tree]] growing 15 to 30 m tall with a trunk diameter of 35 to 60&nbsp;cm. The [[leaf|leaves]] are oppositely arranged and simple with smooth edges. The [[fruit]] is a [[drupe]] containing a single [[seed]].
[[File:Manchester Dock gate.jpg|thumb|right|Greenheart wood was used to build the gate for the Manchester Dock in Liverpool.]] The cyclic bisbenzylisoquinoline [[alkaloid]] [[rodiasine]] was first isolated from this species. The wood is extremely hard and strong, so hard that it cannot be worked with standard tools. It is durable in marine conditions, so it is used to build docks and other structures, and it was an early choice for [[fly fishing|fly fishing rods]]. An estimated 15 to 28% of the original population has been harvested. The species' use as a commercial timber began in the late 18th century, but most of the harvesting has taken place since the introduction of [[chainsaw]]s in 1967.
The ''[[Fram]]'' and the ''[[Endurance (1912 ship)|Endurance]]'', made famous in the polar expeditions of [[Roald Amundsen|Amundsen]] and [[Ernest Shackleton|Shackleton]], were the two strongest wooden ships ever constructed and were sheathed in greenheart to prevent them from being crushed by ice.
Greenheart wood is often sought for construction projects in parts of the Caribbean, where [[wood ants]] are problematic in conventional pine wood construction. It was also used to build the dock gates in [[Liverpool]], such as the [[Manchester Dock (Liverpool)|Manchester dock]] gate.
