[[File:United States installed wind power capacity animation 561px.gif|thumb|Installed wind power capacity]] [[Wind power]] has been growing in the United States since the 1970s.{{weasel inline|date=September 2016}}
==History== The growth of [[wind power in the United States]] has been enhanced by a [[Tax credit#Renewable Energy/Production Tax Credit (PTC)|production tax credit]] (PTC), which pays 2.3¢/kWh for the first 10 years. Development has been off and on again due to the expiration and late renewal of the PTC.<ref>[http://energy.gov/savings/renewable-electricity-production-tax-credit-ptc Renewable Electricity Production Tax Credit (PTC)]</ref> It expired at the end of 2013,<ref>[https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2014/07/17/dead-air-end-to-tax-credits-takes-big-bite-out-of-wind-power Dead Air: End of Tax Credit Deflates Wind Power]</ref><ref>[http://www.gwec.net/index.php?id=121 United States]</ref> only to be restored in December 2014.<ref>[http://www.rechargenews.com/wind/1386834/Update-US-Senate-approves-one-year-wind-PTC-extension Update: US Senate approves one-year wind PTC extension]</ref> In 2015 it was renewed but is phased out over a five-year period.<ref>[http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/renewables-boom-expected-thanks-to-tax-credit/ Renewables Boom Expected Thanks to Tax Credit]</ref> One of the goals set by the [[United States Department of Energy|Department of Energy]] is to increase the number of states which have over 1,000 MW of wind power to 15 by 2018. By the end of 2015 there were 17. Another goal was to increase the number of states with at least 100 MW to 30 by 2010. As of 2011, there are 29.<ref>[http://www1.eere.energy.gov/wind/mission.html Mission, Vision, and Goals]</ref> The 2015 vision for wind calls for 10% generation by wind by 2020 (113 GW), 30% by 2030 (224 GW), and 35% by 2050 (404 GW). It calls for 40 states to each have at least 1 GW, and wind power in all 50 states. Larger wind turbines has expanded the commercial viability of wind to all 50 states.<ref>[http://energy.gov/eere/wind/maps/wind-vision Wind Vision: A New Era for Wind Power in the United States]</ref> Analysts expect 25 GW more between 2016-18.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.transmissionhub.com/articles/2016/03/while-investment-may-slow-in-coming-years-plenty-of-transmission-construction-investment-happening.html |title=While investment may slow in coming years, plenty of transmission construction, investment happening |author=Corina Rivera Linares |publisher= |accessdate=22 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160530102813/http://www.transmissionhub.com/articles/2016/03/while-investment-may-slow-in-coming-years-plenty-of-transmission-construction-investment-happening.html |archive-date=30 May 2016 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
