'''Ore-pine''' ({{lang-no|malmfuru}}; {{lang-sv|malmfura}}; {{lang-da|malmfyr}}; {{lang-is|málmfura}}) is a cured [[pine]]wood used extensively in the [[Middle Ages]] in the construction of [[Scandinavia]]n [[stave church]]es. Ore-pine is the [[heartwood]] of prepared [[old-growth forest|old-growth]] mountain pines; the trees had their branches removed and were left to stand, the tree [[resin]]s bleeding upward and out through the cut branches and thus making the heartwood more resinous. The resultant ore-pine is much more resistant to rot and decay, as evidenced by stave churches surviving from the 12th and 13th centuries.<ref>{{cite book |last=Schroeder |first=Gary |date=2003 |title=The Log Home Maintenance Guide |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QLZFhBuzf8kC |location=Woodstick, Vermont |publisher=The Countryman Press |page=7 |isbn=0-88150-585-4}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1989 |title=Muir's Original Log Home Guide for Builders and Buyers |volume=1 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WH4qAQAAMAAJ |location= |publisher=Muir Publications |page=302 |isbn=}}</ref>

