{{Other uses|Psamathe (disambiguation){{!}}Psamathe}}
{{Greek myth (sea)}}

'''Psamathe''' ([[Ancient Greek]]: Ψάμαθη, from ψάμαθος "sand of the sea-shore"<ref>[[Robert Graves]]. ''[[The Greek Myths]] (1960)''</ref>) was a [[Nereid]] in [[Greek mythology]], i.e., one of the fifty daughters of [[Nereus]] and [[Doris (mythology)|Doris]]. The goddess of sand beaches, Psamathe was the wife of [[Proteus]]<ref>In [[Euripides]]' tragedy ''[[Helen (play)|Helen]]'', Psamathe is married to king [[Proteus of Egypt]].</ref> and the mother of [[Phocus]] by [[Aeacus]].<ref>[[Ovid]]. ''Metamorphoses'', XI, 398.</ref>

Some translations of Ovid have the name as '''Psamanthe'''.<ref>[http://etext.lib.virginia.edu/latin/ovid/sandys/11comm.htm Ovid Illustrated: The Renaissance Reception of Ovid in Image and Text].</ref>

==In modern times==
Psamathe has a [[Psamathe (moon)|moon]] named after her.

